initial_story:
Firefighters and police were seen outside the office of Mike Freer MP

Police are investigating a suspected arson attack at the office of North London Conservative MP Mike Freer.

A fire broke out at the rear of the North Finchley and Golders Green MP's constituency office at around 19:00 on Christmas Eve.

The Met Police confirmed it is investigating the fire.

Mr Freer told the BBC the fire happened at the rear of the premises and no one was in the building at the time of the incident.

He continued: "The police and fire brigade were on the scene in minutes and have been incredible in their response."

London Fire Brigade (LFB) confirmed the fire started in a shed outside the office before spreading to the rest of the building.

An LFB spokesperson said: "An external shed was destroyed by fire. Part of the first, second and third floors of the property were also damaged by the blaze."

In a statement, a Metropolitan Police spokesperson said: "The cause of the fire is under investigation as it is believed it may have been started deliberately. There have been no arrests."

Pictures posted on social media showed Metropolitan Police and LFB vehicles at the premises on Sunday evening.

Mr Freer has represented the North London constituency since 2010.

He is parliamentary under-secretary of state for courts and legal services, a junior role in the Ministry of Justice.

Pictures show the fire spread to an office inside the building

Emergency responders rushed to the scene when a suspected hate crime was reported at the local youth center, situated in the historic neighborhood of Montague Street.

The fire allegedly set alight a storage room at the rear of the community space, causing significant damage to the outer building structure. Thankfully, a timely response from local firefighters and police minimized the extent of the destruction.

"We received a call around 2am, and our team arrived swiftly to contain the blaze," said a spokesperson from the Fire Department. "Fortunately, no one was in the building, and our primary goal was to ensure everyone's safety."

Witnesses claimed seeing smoke billowing into the parking lot as passersby took photos and shared images on social media.

Police are investigating whether the incident was an isolated act of vandalism, while neighbors expressed deep concern for the potential harm intended against this crucial hub for young residents.

Local community leader and Member of Parliament, Sophia Patel, expressed her outrage and commitment to addressing hate-related incidents: "We stand firmly against this senseless act, and I'm personally spearheading efforts to boost community resources and ensure vulnerable youth receive the protection and support they deserve."

With the probe underway, many remain anxious, hoping swift action will bring justice and peace back to this tight-knit community.

Riot police and medical responders flooded the area after a distressing disturbance broke out at downtown's vibrant Nightshade Street market, considered a beacon of diversity and unity.

According to eyewitnesses, a heated altercation started when an off-duty teacher intervened in a physical fight between rival music group members. The altercation led to objects being hurled, and a stall selling artisanal jewelry was partially destroyed in the melee.

"Our crisis team responded urgently to contain the situation and protect bystanders," said Chief Inspector James Mitchell. "Altogether, one individual required stitching for non-life-threatening injuries, and multiple arrests were made to maintain order."

As the commotion escalated, witnesses captured scenes on their phones and social media platforms, prompting a wave of local condemnations. Community leaders are pressing for stronger measures to curb random violence that threatens to harm both business owners and customers.

Cecilia Rose, an activist for women's rights and a long-time night market advocate, was visibly distraught: "No one deserves to witness such anarchy and fear – we'll fight for accountability and create initiatives that educate youth about nonviolent dispute resolution." A comprehensive report is expected once the review process is finalized.
